-- Bank rescue plan sets $100 billion for bank injections
-- 
-- Tue Feb 10, 2009 10:31am EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/02/10/us-financial-bailout-details-sb-idUSTRE5194D520090210

 

 WASHINGTON  (Reuters) - The U.S. Treasury Department's bank rescue plan includes the following spending, according to a source briefed about the plan: 

 * $50 billion for foreclosure mitigation and loan modifications * $100 billion for a "bad bank" public-private partnership that will buy distressed assets. * $100 billion to expand the Federal Reserve's Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF). * $100 billion for bank capital injections following stress-testing by government regulators. * The money will be spent from the Treasury Department's Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP), which currently has about $350 billion in it.